- Technology (i.e., operating parameters, catalysts, rates);

- Equipment (i.e., materials of construction, equipment specifications); and

- Procedures (i.e., emergency response, maintenance, operating) 



The MOC work process does not apply to "replacement in kind", which is defined as a replacement that satisfies the design specifications for the equipment being replaced.



Changes are classified as permanent, temporary, or emergency. Emergency changes are allowed during off-hours and holidays; however, at a minimum, the MOC process requires that the impact of the change on Health and Safety has been assessed, Communication and Training requirements have been met, and when required, a Pre-Start-up Safety Review is to be completed prior to start-up. Temporary changes require the identification of a maximum allowable time frame for the change. An MOC is typically initiated by the individual who has been assigned the task to carry out a proposal as part of the routine work process.



Personnel assess the potential impact of the change on safety and health through a Health and Safety Evaluation procedure for most changes. A HAZOP or What-if/Checklist is conducted for changes that require a more structured evaluation. A Damage Mechanism Review (DMR) and a Hierarchy of Controls Analysis (HCA) are completed for any change that is identified as a Major Change in the Initial Risk Assessment (IRA). 



The following steps are taken to ensure proper implementation of the change:

- Subject matter experts or other employees with technical expertise are involved in making, reviewing or approving the change;

- Equipment is fabricated and installed in accordance with the design specifications;

- Employees whose job tasks are affected by the change are trained prior to the startup of the process;

- Process safety information is updated as necessary; and

- Operating procedures

